§ Definition ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Let $x: Ω → 𝗥$ a random variable and $p: Ω → 𝗥$ a
    distribution. ⦉

  ‖ The ❬mean square❭ of $x$ is $𝗘(x^2)$. ⦉

  ‖ Define $μ = 𝗘(x)$. ⦉

  ‖ We can express $𝗘(x^2) = 𝗘(x)^2 + \cov(x)$ since
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ \begin{aligned} ⦉

      ‖ \cov(x) = 𝗘((x -μ)^2) ⦉

      ‖ ❲&❳= 𝗘(x^2 - 2μx + μ^2) ᜶ ⦉

      ‖ ❲&❳= 𝗘(x^2) -2μ𝗘(x) + μ^2 ᜶ ⦉

      ‖ ❲&❳= 𝗘(x^2) - μ^2. ⦉

      ‖ \end{aligned} ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ We refer to this relation as the ❬mean-variance
    decomposition❭ of $x$.
    † ⦊
      ‖ Future editions will modify this sheet, and likely
        motivate this decomposition in terms of minimum square
        error estimation. ⦉
    ⦉⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ The ❬n’th moment❭ of $x$ is $𝗘(x^n)$. ⦉

  ‖ The mean is the first moment. ⦉

  ‖ The covariance is the second moment minus the square of the
    first moment. ⦉
⦉

